Okay, here we go.<br>
I can speak only for my time in country, JUL '68 to JUL '69, and for the places I was stationed - rear base camp at An Khe, 173rd Airborne HQ at LZ English (2/3 of the way from Qui Nhon to the Quang Ngai Province border), 1/50 Mech Bn HQ outside of Bao Lac in FEB '69.<br><br>
Both booze and drugs were cheap and widely available; though marijuana seemed to be the drug of choice among users.  In my intelligence company, virtually half the unit drank a beer or two after hours.  Just as many stuck to Coke.  One of our senior warrant officers was the only guy I knew who drank hard liquor regularly (borbon straight), but I never saw him drunk.  Never personally saw other troops drunk or up on charges for same; though I had enough cognac and scotch at my promotion party to 1st Lt to float a battleship.  $5 a bottle plus zero tax for Remy Martin &amp; Johnny Walker Red put 10 bottles within reach of my first pay raise.<br><br>
Raw uncut marijuana went for $5/lb in downtown Bong Son, the district capital nearby LZ English.  Getting into 1969, occasionally an unscrupulous merchant would start coating the marijuana with opium if he thought he could hook somebody.  By spring '69, drug cases were 40-45% of the courts martial caseload.  As the MI Company had the largest pool of available junior officers regularly in the rear; we saw most of it.<br><br>
Had two very memorable cases, both as Special Court Martial defanse counsel.  In the first, a young black trooper, originally from the St. Louis ghetto, was charged with possesion of marijauna.  At first he wouldn't talk to me, because I was white.  It took me 3 days to get it through his head that I could care less if he was green and orange striped with purple polka dots.  The day of the trial he had an LSD flashback and had to be hospitalized.  The second was one of 3 cases involving fifths of opium in 70 proof alcohol solution.  Looked like cordovan shoe polish.  The item was confiscated from a soldier's unsecured footlocker that 8 persons had access to.  Though the court convicted; I won an appeal to the general based on the access issue.  I believe the whole squad was probably guilty as sin, but that's not how the case was handled.<br><br>
We shared the base with an ARVN unit. Our portion had 42 bunkers, usually manned by 2nd Battalion soldiers in from the field.  The MPs would make the rounds of these every Sat. morning and come in with marijuana leftovers.  At Bao Lac, a sapper team broke in over a bunker with guys off in happy land.  Fortunately they were the only casualties.  Other damage was limited to 2 trucks, a jeep, and the only building with outside lights on it - the battalion john.  The word we got was they thought it was the tactical operations center.  6 weeks before I left, while perimeter duty officer, found 14 of 42 bunkers asleep.  Have no doubt drugs played a part in that.  Didn't sleep too well after.<br><br>
At a 173rd reunion at Ft. Bragg in 1970, was told by a couple of my former Photo Interpretation Sect men that most of them had done some serios experimentation with marijuana, and that they went to great pains to see to it that I stayed ignorant of the fact, because I too much of a straight arrow  on drugs.<br><br>
One more thing.  I believe it was in August '69 or so that Admiral Thomas Moorer went on TV and told the American people there was no drug problem in Vietnam.  Am still royally pissed over that, even after all these years.  I remember an old Colonel at Ft. Benning telling us young lieutenants that an officer without integrity was only half dressed.  As far as I'm concerned; Moorer was missing his pants that night.
